{
    id: 40,
    chapter: 4,
    verse: 40,
    sanskrit: "अज्ञश्चाश्रद्दधानश्च संशयात्मा विनश्यति |\nनायं लोकोऽस्ति न परो न सुखं संशयात्मन: ||",
    transliteration: "ajñāśh chāśhraddadhānaśh cha saṃśhayātmā vinaśhyati\nnāyaṃ loko ’sti na paro na sukhaṃ saṃśhayātmanaḥ",
    translation: "But ignorant and faithless persons who doubt the revealed scriptures do not attain God consciousness; they fall down. For the doubting soul there is happiness neither in this world nor in the next.",
    purport: `
        <p><strong>1. Disease of Doubt:</strong> Cynical doubt (<em>saṃśhayātmā</em>) is a paralyzing disease. It prevents conviction and action. One who doubts everything cannot reach water because they keep digging new wells but never go deep enough. They "perish" from the spiritual path.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Souring Experience:</strong> Doubt ruins happiness here and hereafter. You cannot enjoy a meal if you doubt it is poison; you cannot enjoy a relationship if you doubt the other person. Doubt is the friction that prevents life from turning smoothly.</p>
        <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Doubt is a luxury the soul cannot afford. Unless we find something to commit to, we remain in perpetual hesitation, denied the joy and progress that only faith-driven action can provide.</p>
    `
},
{
    id: 41,
    chapter: 4,
    verse: 41,
    sanskrit: "योगसंन्यस्तकर्माणं ज्ञानछिन्नसंशयम् |\nआत्मवन्तं न कर्माणि निबध्नन्ति धनञ्जय ||",
    transliteration: "yoga-sannyasta-karmāṇaṃ jñāna-chhinna-saṃśhayam\nātmavantaṃ na karmāṇi nibadnanti dhanañjaya",
    translation: "One who acts in devotional service, renouncing the fruits of his actions, and whose doubts have been destroyed by transcendental knowledge, is situated freely in the self. Thus he is not bound by the reactions of work, O conqueror of riches.",
    purport: `
        <p><strong>1. Final Integration:</strong> The perfected state involves giving up fruits through yoga and destroying doubt through knowledge. Such a person is <em>ātmavantam</em>—situated in the Self. They are no longer reaching out for happiness; they are resting in it.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Karmic Weightlessness:</strong> Actions do not bind such a person. They can act in the world but remain "karmically weightless," like birds flying through the sky without leaving footprints. They are free because their interior is unattached to the exterior.</p>
        <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Unity of Action and Wisdom is the state of perfect freedom. By combining selfless work with steady truth, we sever the chains of our past and become masters of our destiny, acting with boundless energy and zero anxiety.</p>
    `
},
{
    id: 42,
    chapter: 4,
    verse: 42,
    sanskrit: "तस्मादज्ञानसम्भूतं हृत्स्थं ज्ञानअसिनात्मन: |\nछित्त्वैनं संशयं योगमातिष्ठोत्तिष्ठ भारत ||",
    transliteration: "tasmād ajñāna-sambhūtaṃ hṛit-sthaṃ jñānāsinātmanaḥ\nchittvainaṃ saṃśhayaṃ yogam ātiṣhṭhottiṣhṭha bhārata",
    translation: "Therefore the doubts which have arisen in your heart out of ignorance should be slashed by the weapon of knowledge. Armed with yoga, O Bharata, stand up and fight.",
    purport: `
        <p><strong>1. Slaying the Heart-Doubt:</strong> Krishna concludes with a call to action. He identifies doubt as something born of ignorance, situated in the heart like a cancer. He commands Arjuna to use the <em>jñāna-asinā</em> (sword of knowledge) to slash this doubt once and for all.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Stand and Fight:</strong> Wisdom is not for dreaming; it is for living. Once doubt is dead, Arjuna must take refuge in yoga and <em>uttiṣhṭha</em> (stand up). Krishna is telling him that with truth in his mind and detachment in his heart, he is ready to face the world's challenges.</p>
        <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Wisdom is a "weapon for living." The ultimate purpose of our learning is to give us the courage to face our struggles with perfect clarity, turning our internal realization into powerful, righteous action.</p>
    `
}
